%[text] ## 2.4 Discrete Time Controller
%[text] In reality, measurements of the vehicle's state are only available in discrete time, and new commands can only be sent to the propellers at discrete time instants. Convert your continuous time model to a hybrid model where the non-linear dynamics of the vehicle are simulated in continuous time, the full-state measurements are taken at a particular frequency, and the controller computations are performed at a different frequency.
%[text] Note: When state estimation is not performed, these frequencies are typically the same, and **for all the experiments we will collect sensor measurements at 200Hz.**
%%
%[text] In Simulink, this is implemented most easily by adding "Zero-Oder Hold" blocks. Meaning to convert a continuous signal into a discretized one, add a zero-order hold block to the signal line.
%[text] Open the corresponding subsystem in the Simulink drone model:
load_system('exercise02_simulation_model_template')
open_system('exercise02_simulation_model_template/Controller','tab')
%[text] Then add 2 zero-order hold blocks:
%[text] - one to the full state signal line and name it "SensorSampleRate" (this is the sensor signal).
%[text] - one in front of the controller LQR gain matrix and name it "ControllerPace". \
%[text] Note: You do not have to specify the sample rates in the zero-order hold blocks. In similar to the preceeding exercises we will use the app to set the Simulink block parameters using sliders and the set\_param functionality. For example, the code below contains the callback to one of the drop down blocks and the dial block inside the app.
%[text] ```matlabCodeExample
%[text] % Value changed function: ControllerGainsDropDown
%[text] function ControllerGainsDropDownValueChanged(app, event)
%[text]     try
%[text]         switch app.ControllerGainsDropDown.Value
%[text]             case 'cont'
%[text]                 set_param(app.name + "/Controller/LQR gain matrix", 'Gain', mat2str(-app.K_lqr.continous_time));
%[text]             case'20 Hz'
%[text]                 set_param(app.name + "/Controller/LQR gain matrix", 'Gain', mat2str(-app.K_lqr.discrete_time_20Hz));
%[text]             case '50 Hz'
%[text]                 set_param(app.name + "/Controller/LQR gain matrix", 'Gain', mat2str(-app.K_lqr.discrete_time_50Hz));
%[text]             case '100 Hz'
%[text]                 set_param(app.name + "/Controller/LQR gain matrix", 'Gain', mat2str(-app.K_lqr.discrete_time_100Hz));   
%[text]             case '200 Hz'
%[text]                 set_param(app.name + "/Controller/LQR gain matrix", 'Gain', mat2str(-app.K_lqr.discrete_time_200Hz));
%[text]         end
%[text]     catch
%[text]         msgbox("The rate transition blocks have not been implemented correctly.","Warning","warn")
%[text]     end
%[text] end
%[text] 
%[text] % Value changed function: ControllerSpeedHzSpinner
%[text] function ControllerSpeedHzSpinnerValueChanged(app, event)
%[text]     if app.ControllerSpeedHzSpinner.Value == 0.0
%[text]         set_param(app.name + "/Controller/ControllerPace",'Commented','through');
%[text]     else
%[text]         set_param(app.name + "/Controller/ControllerPace/",'OutPortSampleTime',string(round(1/app.ControllerSpeedHzSpinner.Value, 3)),'Commented','off');
%[text]     end
%[text] end
%[text] ```
%%
%[text] Let's now investigate the influence of the controller frequency. Open the app and load the simulink model where you added the rate transistion blocks. Please note there is no need to close the model before you open the app. The app will always use the current state of the model, meaning it will include changes that you have done even if they have not been saved.
PS_Quadcopter_Lab_app; %[output:37696fd9]
%[text] The sample rates of the rate transition blocks can be adjusted using the elements in the exercise panel. For your reference:
%[text] - "Controller Gains": Selects the correct "LQR gain" block for the specified frequency.
%[text] - "Controller Speed \[Hz\]": Sets the computing rate for the LQR gain block (rate transition block).
%[text] - "Sensors" defines the sample rate of full-state "sensor" measurements. \
%%
%[text] Investigate the impact of the signal and controller frequencies. First use the Controller LQR Gains for 200 Hz.
%[text] - How is the step change tracking performance affected by the frequency of control computations?
%[text] - Does the closed loop system become unstable at some frequency?
%[text] - If yes, why and at what frequency? \
%[text] ```
%[text] Write your answer here...
%[text] ```
%[text] Test out the following two combinations:
%[text] - set the controller computations to a frequency of 10Hz, but use the controller parameters designed for 200Hz
%[text] - set the controller computations to a frequency of 10Hz, but use the controller parameters designed for 20Hz.
%[text] - set the controller computations to a frequency of 200 Hz, but use the controller parameters designed for 20 Hz.  \
%[text] Explain the results using intuitive arguments.
%[text] ```
%[text] Write your answer here...
%[text] ```

